LINK END--><br>
<br>
&quot;George Bush is a religious fundamentalist who uses the Old Testament to justify his right to attack other countries, according to a veteran British peace campaigner.&quot;<br>
<br>
I thought this bloke had a lot of interesting points to make...so..I thought I'd share. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.growthspurts.com/drivee/images/434360233606.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=luvthatdyl>LuvThatDyl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 47<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/21/03 3:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Shrub</span><hr size=1> I think this Kent guy had some interesting points, but there were also some inaccuracies.<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;Kent is also infuriated by the US position on Israel - a nation that both has nuclear weapons and has attacked another country, he says.&quot;<br>
<br>
Uh, first of all there is no proof that Israel has nukes.  Second, they have never attacked another country.  This claim is simply false.<br>
<br>
As for the chosen people comment, that is his opinion about what he thinks Bush might think.  Granted, Bush thinks he is pretty special, but I don't recall him referring to the US as the &quot;chosen people&quot;.  As for Jews being referred to as the &quot;chosen people&quot;, that is misconstrued by just about everyone.  &quot;Chosen&quot; just refers to the group who was chosen for the path of the Torah, and it has nothing to do with superiority.  The superiority complex that goes along with this has been made up by people who don't like the Jews, not the Jews themselves.  <br>
<br>
Sorry, I just had to clear those things up.  I get nervous when people make false claims like that because it causes trouble for innocent people.  For the most part, I agree with a lot of what this guy said.  Shrub is like a little kid who was left alone with daddy's Corvette, and he is definitely a fundie.  He may think of himself and this country as &quot;chosen&quot;, but not in the same aspect as the religious Jews.  His is definitely a superiority complex, and in the two years he has been in office he has created way too many enemies around the world.  I wasn't thrilled to have voted for Gore/Lieberman, but I am damn glad I didn't vote for W.  The guy is out of control, and I hope he gets the boot in 2004.<br>
<br>
Stacey <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gaia25>Gaia25</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 109<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/21/03 4:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Shrub</span><hr size=1> Thanks for the corrections about Isreal Stacey...I must admit, I know just enough about the situation to be of the opinion that neither one of them is wholly right or wrong.<br>
<br>
As for the &quot;chosen people&quot; stuff...It wouldn't suprise me if Bush did think that Americans are &quot;special&quot; or &quot;above it all&quot; in some way...but I wouldn't think the average American feels that way.<br>
<br>
I thought that he made some interesting points...but mostly came off as a bit of a fundie himself - just a different kind! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.growthspurts.com/drivee/images/434360233606.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=filfilksq>filfilksq</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/21/03 8:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Israel and Nuclear weapons</span><hr size=1> &quot;Uh, first of all there is no proof that Israel has nukes. &quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.fas.org/nuke/guide/israel/nuke/">www.fas.org/nuke/guide/israel/nuke/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Second, they have never attacked another country.&quot;<br>
<br>
I think that is a question of interpretation.  Some say invaded, some say it's &quot;defense&quot;.<br>
<br>
Kate <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=filfilksq>filfilksq</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 37<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/21/03 8:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Nuclear Weapons</span><hr size=1> Quote from the article:<br>
<br>
&quot;&quot;We've got eight or nine countries with nuclear weapons and those countries all say nuclear weapons are essential for security as we do in Britain. What's the moral logic in saying other people can't?&quot; <br>
<br>
I think it matters which country.. yes, Pakistan and India both have nuclear weapons, and that scares the bejeebus out of me, because they are so volatile.. I have to say the same for any country in the region, no matter how &quot;reasonable&quot; or &quot;democratic&quot; they purport to be.<br>
<br>
Kate <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fireofpsyche>fire of psyche</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Goddess of the Matrix</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/21/03 9:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.rialian.com/elvens~1.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear Weapons</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>no matter how &quot;reasonable&quot; or &quot;democratic&quot; they purport to be.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Plenty of people probably say the same thing about us and our nuclear arsenal &amp; chemical weapons.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gaia25>Gaia25</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 110<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/22/03 4:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear Weapons</span><hr size=1> I'm one of those people who finds it really scary that *any* country has them.<br>
<br>
Surely if we want one country to get rid of them, then we should all commit to doing the same?? <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.growthspurts.com/drivee/images/434360233606.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=filfilksq>filfilksq</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 38<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/22/03 8:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear Weapons</span><hr size=1> I misspoke, I completely agree with you!<br>
<br>
Kate <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=luvthatdyl>LuvThatDyl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 48<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/22/03 11:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Israel</span><hr size=1> I should probably make myself clear on the nukes thing. There is no proof that Israel has nukes, but there is definitely a lot of speculation.  I don't deny that they have them, but there is still no proof that they have them.  The reason why I took issue with the man being quoted in the article is because he wasn't saying &quot;I think Israel has them&quot;, instead he was suggesting that Bush should snub them because they do have them.  That is a lofty accusation with no proof.  I wouldn't blame them for having nukes due to the fact that their sovereignty is at risk everyday, but I'm in agreement with the rest of the people here that no country should have them, not even the US.  I'm not as worried about Israel having them due to being a civilzed democracy, but as Bush is showing us, even a civilized democracy can get a little out of hand.  I wouldn't lose sleep over Israel having nukes, but I would lose sleep over someplace like Iraq having them.  It is wrong in both situations, but one situation is a little scarier than the other.  <br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;I think that is a question of interpretation. Some say invaded, some say it's &quot;defense&quot;.&quot;<br>
<br>
I don't personally feel there is much to interpret here.  I'm guessing he is referring to the 1967 war.  In that situation 4 countries surrounded the border and publicly announced the attack on the radio stations throughout the Middle East.  They were cocky about it because they thought there was no way they could lose.  Israel didn't wipe out Egypts air force by going into Egypt and finding all the planes.  They wiped out the air force because the air force was right there ready to attack.  Israel would have been completely stupid not to take the first shot.  However, everyone was in place already, and there was absolutely no question over whether they were going to be attacked.  If you tell me that you are going to kill me, then you go around town telling everyone that you are going to come to my house on a certain day to kill me, then you step onto my front lawn with a gun, well, I'm not going to wait for you to take the first shot.  I'm going to do something to protect my family.  If I was to turn around and shoot you as you were coming towards me with your weapon, then I don't think people would accuse me of being the aggressor.  For some reason there is a double standard where Israel is concerned.  I disagree with a lot of their tactics, but I don't see a whole lot of interpretation surrounding the 1967 war.  Besides, they have already turned over more than 90% of the land they seized during that war in exchange for peace with Egypt.  They had even built on this land already.  If they were just interested in taking land, then the Sinai would still belong to Israel.  Instead, they gave it back and just said &quot;here is your land, leave us alone now&quot;.  All they want is to be left alone.<br>
<br>
Stacey <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=filfilksq>filfilksq</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 39<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/22/03 12:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Israel</span><hr size=1> &quot;There is no proof that Israel has nukes, but there is definitely a lot of speculation.&quot;<br>
<br>
Sounds like Iraq.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm not as worried about Israel having them due to being a civilzed democracy&quot;<br>
<br>
I'm worried because they seem to have no hesitation in using heavy artillery (helicopter gunships, guided missles, etc.) in civilian areas.  They are targeting one or two alleged terrorists, but take out double or triple (or more) that amount in so-called &quot;collateral damage&quot;.  If they were able to design a nuclear weapon that could guarantee the safety of greater Israel, do you think they would hesitate to use it?  I don't.  What frightens me is those most likely to act this way are the people who keep getting elected to high office there.. I understand the Israeli people are desperate, but this, in my opinion, is not the way a &quot;civilized democracy&quot; should operate.  Recently they've begun demolishing Palestinian stores and shops that they say did not have &quot;proper permits&quot; to be there.. I think that's an excuse.  I think many of the policies are there simply to try and break the spirit of the Palestinians, and I think that's wrong and it's going to backfire.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=luvthatdyl>LuvThatDyl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 51<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/22/03 1:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Israel</span><hr size=1> &quot;They are targeting one or two alleged terrorists, but take out double or triple (or more) that amount in so-called &quot;collateral damage&quot;.&quot;<br>
<br>
This is one area where I agree with you.  I understand that Israel is always the guinea pig when it comes to dealing with the war on terror, and therefore more likely to make the mistakes that come under scrutiny, but I don't agree with bombing areas that have the potential to house innocent children.  I was appalled when they killed the Hamas leader in that apartment and took out 14 children with him.  Israelis were appalled as well.  It isn't like taking out this one leader had the potential to save lives because there was another one to rise up and take his place.  Meanwhile, more innocent children died as a result.  I understand that they would be prone to making the most mistakes, but I do feel that some situations are just common sense.<br>
<br>
&quot;If they were able to design a nuclear weapon that could guarantee the safety of greater Israel, do you think they would hesitate to use it? I don't.&quot;<br>
<br>
Yes, they would hesitate to use it.  That doesn't mean they won't use it, but keep in mind that this nation is a democracy that has to answer to voters and the international community.  Contrary to belief throughout the Arab world, Israelis are not monsters.  Many of them protest Israel's actions as it is, and many of them go out of their way to stand up for the rights of the Palestinians.  If Israel just wanted to wipe out the Palestinians, then it would have been done a long time ago.  They have the means to do it, and definitely have the excuse in place.  If they could defeat 4 countries in 1967, who were backed at the time by the second most powerful nation in the world(Russia), then they could definitely wipe out the people in these territories that don't have their own military, and who only have the backing of nations that Israel has defeated before.  <br>
<br>
&quot;What frightens me is those most likely to act this way are the people who keep getting elected to high office there.. I understand the Israeli people are desperate, but this, in my opinion, is not the way a &quot;civilized democracy&quot; should operate.&quot;<br>
<br>
I'm not crazy about Sharon either, but let's put ourselves in Israel's place for a moment.  If we had either a successful or attempted 9/11 every single day, then we would be desperate.  If we thought that someone like Pat Buchanan had a never before used tactic that might protect us, then in our desperation we would end up electing him.  We have the luxury of looking at 9/11 as a moment in our lives instead of a way of life, and therefore we can be more critical.  If it was your child having to attend a kindergarten with an armed guard outside the door, then you just might be desperate enough to vote someone in who you think would protect your child at all costs.  Is voting for Sharon the rational answer?  No.  But these voters don't share his sentiments, just the desperation.  Looking at it from the outside, I think the rational answer would be to vote in someone who followed in Rabin's footsteps.<br>
<br>
&quot;Recently they've begun demolishing Palestinian stores and shops that they say did not have &quot;proper permits&quot; to be there.. I think that's an excuse. I think many of the policies are there simply to try and break the spirit of the Palestinians, and I think that's wrong and it's going to backfire.&quot;<br>
<br>
I agree with you that it is wrong to demolish Palestinian property like this, but it isn't being done to &quot;break the spirit of the Palestinians&quot;.  It is an irrational act of desperation to try and deter the terrorists from continuing with their actions.  If someone thinks they are going to be rewarded in the afterlife by blowing up Israeli civilians, then they aren't going to hesitate to do it.  However, if they think their family will suffer by losing their home or business, then they might think twice.  I don't agree with this tactic, and it is a prime example of how the ends don't justify the means.  However, it is not being done to merely break anyone's spirit.  People don't think of Palestinians as having &quot;spirit&quot; because the majority of the community supports terrorist activity, and when the terrorist succeeds, they throw a party.  When a Jewish terrorist gets caught trying to blow up Palestinians, then Israel doesn't throw a parade and call them a martyr, they lock the person's butt in jail and throw away the key.  This also applies to soldiers who overstep their bounds and take their actions to a personal level.  Israel already tried to boost the &quot;spirit&quot; of the Palestinians by building them 4 universities and providing them with modern amenities like utilities.  As of 1967 the vast majority of Palestinians living in the territories didn't even have utilities.  Jordan and Egypt left these people hanging out to dry.  For many of them, they wouldn't have homes or businesses to lose if it wasn't for the Israelis.  This doesn't make it right for Israel to turn around and take these things away, but if Israel was really trying to break their spirit, then they would be living in worse conditions than they were under Jordan and Egypt, if that is possible.  If the Palestinians would cease the terror activity, then they could be living free just like the Arabs within the Israel borders.  If acts of terror are considered &quot;spirit&quot;, then I suppose I don't want them to have &quot;spirit&quot; either.  <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=filfilksq>filfilksq</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/22/03 2:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Israel</span><hr size=1> &quot;keep in mind that this nation is a democracy that has to answer to voters and the international community.&quot;<br>
<br>
The voters, yes.. the international community, I think that except for the US they could care less what the International community thinks.  There have been countless calls from the international community on various issues, and they are usually ignored.  I'm not saying they don't have the right to do that, I just think your comment is misleading.<br>
<br>
&quot;People don't think of Palestinians as having &quot;spirit&quot; because the majority of the community supports terrorist activity, and when the terrorist succeeds, they throw a party. When a Jewish terrorist gets caught trying to blow up Palestinians, then Israel doesn't throw a parade and call them a martyr, they lock the person's butt in jail and throw away the key. This also applies to soldiers who overstep their bounds and take their actions to a personal level.&quot;<br>
<br>
When I talk about spirit, I mean the will to survive, to have a life for their families, to have freedom and independence.  When a terrorist activity happens, I don't think most of them enjoy the terrorist part, but celebrate the activity part.  As with the Israelis, they are just happy somebody is doing something.. but I think the realization of what this means on a human level will come back to haunt them.  If you read some of the accounts, I believe most of this &quot;terrorism party&quot; stuff is perpetrated by the Suicide Brigade itself.  The general theme I've come across is that the families don't even know their kids are involved, until a bombing happens and they come home to find members from the Suicide Brigade there setting up a party... I think a lot of this is built up by this extremist group, and the people feel hopelessly caught up in it (kind of like Hitler, huh?).<br>
<br>
..and I also don't believe it's entirely accurate that Israelis are so circumspect about their own terrorists, the grave of the settler in Hebron comes to mind.. I think they still have annual pilgrimmages to his gravesite etc. etc.  I've also read many accounts of atrocities by soldiers, and the line is always &quot;well, it was unavoidable&quot; for one reason or another, or &quot;we're looking into that&quot; but you never here about it again, or &quot;we thought there was a terrorist there so we looted the house&quot;, that kind of thing.  I'm not saying the PA is any better (it's probably a lot worse), but I don't think they are on an equal par as to what they can do, the level of control they have, or the level of international recognition.  If you're going to call yourself a civilized democracy, I think you have a lot more to live up to.<br>
<br>
&quot;If the Palestinians would cease the terror activity, then they could be living free just like the Arabs within the Israel borders.&quot;<br>
<br>
How &quot;free&quot; are they really?  How are they regarded inside Israel, as beloved members of society or second-class citizens?<br>
<br>
I think this is one of the worst situations in the world, and I for one can't come up with any kind of reasonable solution.  I wish some university somewhere would have a contest for ideas to end the conflict, and maybe we'd get some fresh ideas.. it seems we keep hashing out the same old, tired, ideas over and over again, that have never worked and never will work.<br>
<br>
And on that depressing note, lol... <br>
