<br>
It isn't that they don't care what the international community thinks.  Israel has diplomatic relations with most non-Arab nations.  The problem is that when another nation makes a recommendation to Israel, it isn't in Israel's best interest.  European nations are afraid of the Arab nations because of the terrorism and the oil.  US has the ability to strong-arm the Arab nations, but other places don't.  Israel is the only nation that is told to &quot;show restraint&quot; when they are attacked.  No other nation in the world would be asked to do such a thing.  This is why Israel sometimes needs to do what they feel is necessary despite what others have to say.  If they decided to &quot;show restraint&quot;, then they would be obliterated.  However, Israel doesn't just blow off the international community either.  Nuking their neighbors would definitely be crossing the line, and Israel knows that.  They have been accused of a lot of things, but stupidity isn't one of them.  They are just in a predicament where they have to walk a fine line between diplomatic relations and protecting their citizens.  They also realize that there are those in the international community that help them, and they can't afford to lose that.  For instance, Germany is providing them with a missile defense system in order to protect themselves from Iraq if the US invades.  Great Britain also provides them with a lot of military equipment.  If they piss off the US and Europe by breaking out the nukes, then they have way too much to lose.  As supportive as America is of Israel, most citizens wouldn't stand for Israel starting a nuclear war.  <br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;If you're going to call yourself a civilized democracy, I think you have a lot more to live up to.&quot;<br>
<br>
One can say the same thing about any civilized democracy.  US soldiers have done some terrible things as well, but nobody questions our civilized or democratic status.  Israeli soldiers do some bad things while following orders, but if a soldier oversteps those bounds and starts going outside their duties, then that soldier usually gets thrown in jail.  There are also many things soldiers get accused of, and then it comes out later that it wasn't true.  That isn't true in all cases, but it happens quite a bit during the &quot;smear Israel&quot; campaigns.  Some of these accusations are from the same sources that claim Jews sacrifice Christians and Muslims to drink their blood, which BTW is specifically prohibited by Jewish law.  <br>
<br>
&quot;How &quot;free&quot; are they really? How are they regarded inside Israel, as beloved members of society or second-class citizens?&quot;<br>
<br>
First of all, they are freer in Israel than any other place in the Arab world.  Each Arab individual has the right to vote, freedom of religion, freedom of speech, ability for all citizens to get an education, career choices for both men and women, etc.  Second, they are considered equal members of society by many.  I know they have the same problems there that minorities in most countries have.  I think that is human nature.  However, Arabs have the same opportunities as the Jews, Arabs are elected to the Knesset and many Arabs and Jews intermingle.  An Arab and a Jewish family being friends in Israel isn't anymore unusual than a black family and a whilte family being friends in the US.  The reason why it is so important to keep the Jewish majority is because the whole concept behind the creation of Israel was to guarantee Jewish people a safe haven.  If they lose the Jewish majority, then the Jews are back to square one with persecution, slaughter and exile.  This isn't to hurt the Arab, but to save the Jew.  The government also tries to be inclusive of Arabs.  They recently put up bilingual signs throughout Tel Aviv so the Arab population could get around easier.  Their voice is being heard, but like any other minority, there are various issues that come about.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I think this is one of the worst situations in the world, and I for one can't come up with any kind of reasonable solution. I wish some university somewhere would have a contest for ideas to end the conflict, and maybe we'd get some fresh ideas.. it seems we keep hashing out the same old, tired, ideas over and over again, that have never worked and never will work.&quot;<br>
<br>
I soooo agree with you.  I sometimes wonder if this perpetual cycle of violence will ever end.  I personally think that a two state solution is a good idea, but that the PA needs serious reforms first, and there needs to be some sort of guarantee for Israel's safety.  Jordan and Egypt have managed to achieve peace with Israel, eventhough I wouldn't call everyone friends.  That gives me some hope for settling the conflict.  I don't see it being settled anytime too soon though.  Sharon and Arafat are both too dangerous, and they have too many little personal games going.  Hey, they should put you and me in charge.  We can respectfully debate without hating and killing eachother, lol.  Its too bad Einstein had to turn down the Israeli presidency when it was offered.  Maybe he would have thought of something back then.  &lt;sigh&gt;<br>
<br>
<br>
Stacey<br>
