<br>
As for making the Pals Israeli citizens, I believe you are right.  That isn't going to fly with either side.  Israel can't risk losing a Jewish majority because of the fact they are a democracy.  If the majority are Arab/Palestinian, then they will vote in Arab/Palestinian leaders.  Once that happens, they run the risk of the country being transformed into a nation that is just like the other nations in the Middle East.  Not only do the citizens in general lose their freedoms as a result, but the Jewish citizens wouldn't be safe.  They would either be exiled like they were in other Muslim countries, or they would be executed.  At least this is the risk that is run if the Jews lose their majority.  As for the Palestinian side, I don't think they would be too keen on becoming Israeli citizens.  They already had the option of living under Israeli rule in the territories, and they don't like that option.  Making them citizens would bring them back to square one.  The only thing that will help is to end the cycle of violence, but both sides have differing opinions on who needs to take the first step on that.  I personally feel that the violence started with the Pals, and that they need to take the first step to end it.  I feel that if Israel just withdraws all troops, then the Pals will just escalate the violence because nobody would stop them.  I'm sure you feel just the opposite as me, but I could be wrong about that too.  I just hope it doesn't get worse before it gets better. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showPrevMessage?topicID=84.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showNextMessage?topicID=84.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topic